                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>A mixed bag:</em></strong><em> In the <a href="http://www.consortiuminfo.org/bulletins/feb06.php">last issue</a> last  issue I highlighted the head-butting in standards relating to the digital home,  and especially in the wireless space.&nbsp;  That process has continued apace since then, with confrontations  continuing not only in the wireless sector, but in the powerline data  transmission space as well.&nbsp; Still, as  featured in the first article below, not all was war: in the mesh space,  proponents of rival proposals WiMA and SEEMesh made nice, and linked arms to  move forward in order to populate our homes with networks of close-range  software radios, the better to serve us.</em></p>                      </td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.commentwire.com/article_news.asp?guid=1E5178A3-0FD0-4456-9744-48C449A2A723" target="_hdl">Wireless mesh standard emerges as  rivals bury hatchet<br>
              </a>ComputerBusinessReview.com March 16, 2006</strong>&nbsp;  A standard for WLAN mesh networking has moved significantly closer after two  groups with rival proposals agreed to merge and present a common front, not  least because they both need to address the challenge of WiMAX....Perhaps  drawing on the bitter experience of ultra-wideband (UWB) technology, where  standardization efforts were called off by the IEEE in January failure of the  two rivals there to agree, last week WiMA and SEEMesh asked for and received  permission from the standards body to attempt a common proposal. That proposal  was forged, and has now been accepted by IEEE as the basis on which work can  proceed. <a href="http://www.commentwire.com/article_news.asp?guid=1E5178A3-0FD0-4456-9744-48C449A2A723">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style10"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://dataweek.co.za/article.asp?pklArticleId=3853&pklIssueId=522&pklCategoryId=31" target="_hdl">First specification of standard  formalises powerline communications<br>
              </a>Press Release</strong><br>
              <strong>Opera March 24, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The Open PLC European Research Alliance  (Opera) today announced the development and approval of the first open global  specification for Powerline Communications (PLC) access, also known as  Broadband over Powerline (BPL).This specification will accelerate mass rollout  of high-speed, low-cost, broadband access, voice and audiovisual services, as  well as utility applications for control and management operations....The Opera  PLC specification will be promoted through international standardisation  organisations, including IEEE and ETSI. <a href="http://dataweek.co.za/article.asp?pklArticleId=3853&pklIssueId=522&pklCategoryId=31">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style10"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.telecomweb.com/news/1140640599.htm" target="_hdl">OPERAtic Dissonance: BPL Battle Brews<br>
              </a>TelecomWeb.com March 6, 2006</strong>&nbsp;Europe&rsquo;s Open  PLC European Research Alliance (OPERA) formally announced development and  approval of what it calls &ldquo;the first open global specification for Powerline  Communications (PLC) access,&rdquo; a specification based largely on technology from  Spain&rsquo;s Design of Systems on Silicon S.A. (DS2). The move sets the stage for an  expected world war over broadband over powerline (BPL) standards that will pit  the OPERA specification against those from the competing American HomePlug  Powerline Alliance. <a href="http://www.telecomweb.com/news/1140640599.htm">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <div align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font>              </div>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://home.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20060303005629&newsLang=en" target="_hdl">HomePlug Powerline Alliance Announces  Comprehensive, Global Compliance, Interoperability and Coexistence Strategy<br>
              </a>Press Release</strong><br>
              <strong>Business Wire March 6, 2006</strong>&nbsp;SAN RAMON, Calif - Driving the adoption  of open-standards based powerline communications technologies, the HomePlug(R)  Powerline Alliance today announced a robust compliance, interoperability and  coexistence program....this strategy includes a certification process, a  Plugfest event and proactive efforts to maintain coexistence and  interoperability with existing products and other powerline standards.... The  HomePlug Powerline Alliance has taken key measures to guarantee coexistence  between the emerging HomePlug AV technology and the existing installed base of  more than 4.5 million HomePlug 1.0 devices worldwide....&quot;Coexistence with  other powerline technologies is effective only if multiple competitive  powerline solutions on the same wire have agreed to a standardized mechanism.  In this environment, coexistence must be defined in a globally recognized open  standards body to ensure worldwide deployment. The HomePlug Alliance is working  in the IEEE and ETSI to achieve this coexistence and interoperability  goal.&quot; <a href="http://home.businesswire.com/portal/site/google/index.jsp?ndmViewId=news_view&newsId=20060303005629&newsLang=en">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.wirelessweek.com/article/CA6315082.html" target="_hdl">MIMO Clears Another Hurdle<br>
              </a>Brad Smith</strong><br>
              <strong>News@2 Direct/WirelessWeek.com March 12, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The next, fast  generation of Wi-Fi using MIMO (multiple-input, multiple output) technology  reached a major standardization milestone today. The IEEE working group gave  its tentative approval to a draft 1.0 standard for the much-discussed 802.11n  specification. Bill McFarland, chief technology officer with Atheros  Communications, says the working group members will take 40 days to make  comments and vote on the proposed standard. If it is approved by at least 75  percent of the members, the proposal will be submitted to the IEEE in July. <a href="http://www.wirelessweek.com/article/CA6315082.html">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style10">Open Document Update </p>
