                <tr>
                  <td colspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>The ODF Alliance will  work to enable governments around the world to have greater control over and  direct management of their documents, now and forever [March 6, 2006]</em></strong></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td width="46" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td width="455" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p>Ken Wasch, president  of ODF Alliance founding member Software &amp; Information Industry Association</p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>Things are popping again:&nbsp; </em></strong><em>After a quiet  February, both sides in the ODF &ndash; XML format competition were back in action  with a vengeance, as each rolled out new initiatives in an effort to win the  hearts and minds of the marketplace, and sometimes took more direct actions as  well.&nbsp; The month's announcements  included a new organization (the ODF Alliance) to educate governments about the  wonders of ODFand a new OASIS initiative called the ODF Adoption Committee, on  the one hand, and aXML Formats developers support organization called the Open  XML Formats Developer Group, on the other.</em></p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.linux-watch.com/news/NS2741539029.html" target="_hdl">Microsoft's anti-ODF battle continues<br>
                </a>Steven J. Vaughan-Nichols</strong><br>
                <strong>Linux-Watch.com March 23, 2006</strong>&nbsp;...A Microsoft representative  explained that Microsoft was not on the committee to slow down or block the  ODF's path to becoming an ODF standard. Instead, she said, &quot;Jim Thatcher  is part of Microsoft's team working on the Office Open XML File Format  standardization process. That process involves working closely with TC-45 of  the ECMA standards body as well as JTC1 SC 34 for the ISO standardization  process.&quot; <a href="http://www.linux-watch.com/news/NS2741539029.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.irishdev.com/NewsArticle.aspx?id=2118" target="_hdl">Irish OpenDocument Format Alliance<br>
              </a>Fergal Breen</strong><br>
              <strong>Irish Development.com March 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;As documents and services are  increasingly transformed from paper to electronic form, there is growing  recognition that governments and their constituents may not be able to access,  retrieve and use critical records, information and documents in the future. A  broad cross-section of associations, academic institutions, industry and  related groups today joined together to form the OpenDocument Format Alliance (ODF  Alliance), an organization dedicated to promoting open solutions to this  problem. <a href="http://www.irishdev.com/NewsArticle.aspx?id=2118">...Full Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://searchopensource.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid39_gci1171615,00.html" target="_hdl">OASIS gives Microsoft Office another  punch with ODF Adoption Committee<br>
              </a>Jack Loftus</strong><br>
              <strong>SearchOpenSource/TechTarget March 8, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The smoke had not yet  cleared from last week's OpenDocument Alliance news when a new group called the  OASIS OpenDocument Adoption Committee fired a fresh volley against proprietary  file standards. The committee includes representatives of IBM, Novell Inc., and  Sun Microsystems Inc., as well as government agencies like the National  Informatics Centre of the Government of India and the Netherlands Tax and  Customs Administration. Its intended purpose is to raise awareness of Open  Document Format (ODF) and similar open standards to the point where a truly  open file format can be provided as a robust alternative to proprietary formats  like Microsoft Office. <a href="http://searchopensource.techtarget.com/originalContent/0,289142,sid39_gci1171615,00.html">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://news.zdnet.co.uk/software/applications/0,39020384,39256019,00.htm" target="_hdl">Group launched to promote OpenDocument  in government<br>
              </a>Ingrid Marson</strong><br>
              <strong>ZDNet UK March 7, 2006</strong>&nbsp;A number of companies and industry  associations have joined forces to promote the use of the OpenDocument standard  in the public sector....&quot;The new group is focused on government adoption  of ODF &mdash; notwithstanding the fact that there is only one government member &mdash;  the Information and Communications Technology [department] for the City of  Vienna &mdash; so far,&quot; he wrote, in his standards blog.Despite the current lack  of government support, Updegrove seemed positive about the impact the alliance  could have on public sector organisations that are considering a move to  OpenDocument. &quot;The proposed activities of the ODF Alliance will provide  useful support that those who wish to implement ODF at the municipal, state and  government level can draw upon,&quot; he said. <a href="http://news.zdnet.co.uk/software/applications/0,39020384,39256019,00.htm">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
