              <table width="605"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td width="560" valign="top" bgcolor="#C4EECE" class="style2"><p><strong><em>Just when you thought that open source was  becoming too commercialized:</em></strong><em>&nbsp; The &quot;free&quot; in &quot;free and open  software&quot; starts to begin to look a bit oxymoronic when you observe how  strong a bear hug big business has given to software like Linux.&nbsp; As the next two articles indicate, Linux can  be a big profit maker for companies like IBM, and can steer the investment of  others like Intel.&nbsp; But just when it  seems like open source has been sold out, you read an article like the third  one appearing below, and are reminded that to the third world, &quot;free&quot;  is still a very important and meaningful word.</em></p></td>
                </tr>
              </table>
              <p class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.infoworld.nl/idgns/bericht.phtml?id=002570DE00740E184825713200085F00" target="_hdl">Linux a lovely little earner for IBM<br>
              </a>Randal Jackson</strong><br>
              <strong>InfoWorld.com March 17, 2006</strong>&nbsp;IBM Corp.&rsquo;s business built around  Linux was worth US$16 billion last year and is projected to be worth more than  US$50 billion in total, said the company&rsquo;s global head of public sector Linux  sales, Mary Ann Fisher. &ldquo;Governments worldwide are spending more than US$3  billion a year on Linux hardware, software and services, and this is growing at  35 percent a year,&rdquo; she said. &ldquo;But it&rsquo;s the U.S. military that is spending the  most. They view it as a source of innovation.&rdquo; <a href="http://www.infoworld.nl/idgns/bericht.phtml?id=002570DE00740E184825713200085F00">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.internetnews.com/dev-news/article.php/3590406" target="_hdl">Itanium Alliance Invests in Linux<br>
              </a>David Needle</strong><br>
              <strong>InternetNews.com March 10, 2006</strong>&nbsp;SAN FRANCISCO -- The Itanium  Solutions Alliance still won't say much about its plans to spend a $10 billion  kitty announced in January, but it did identify one project it's spending a  tiny fraction of that money on. In a collaboration with Gelato, the ISA said  it's giving money to help optimize open source compilers for Linux-based  Itanium platforms. Gelato is a global technical community focused on advancing  Linux on the Intel Itanium platform. It was co-founded by HP and seven research  institutions. <a href="http://www.internetnews.com/dev-news/article.php/3590406">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style2"><strong><a href="http://www.egovmonitor.com/node/5191" target="_hdl">Free software in developing countries  vital to future prosperity and good governance<br>
              </a>United Nations University</strong><br>
              <strong>eGovMonitor.com March 21, 2006</strong>&nbsp;The growth of free, open-source  software presents developing countries with an opportunity to escape from  technological dependence on developed countries, but also a challenge to build  up local expertise, United Nations University experts say....UNU experts and  others widely believe that Linux and open source solutions will find their  biggest markets in developing countries, particularly China, East Asia, India  and South America. While the use of open source software continues to grow in  developing countries, there remains a problem of very few open source  programmers in these same developing countries.... Some examples [of home grown  open source applications] are: Online Delivery of Land Titles in India, Citizen  Service Centers in Brazil, Philippine Customs Reform or ICT-based Electoral  Reform in South Africa. Innovative solutions based on open-source technologies  enable faster diffusion of ICT. <a href="http://www.egovmonitor.com/node/5191">...Full  Story</a></p>
              <p align="center" class="style2"><font size="2" face="Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif"><img src="/bulletins/sep.gif" alt="spacer" width="203" height="23"></font></p>
              <p align="left" class="style10"><strong>China</strong></p>
              <table width="508"  border="0" align="center" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="1">
                <tr>
                  <td colspan="2" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p class="style79"><strong><em>We express our indignation and resolute  opposition against IEEE and its agents for their complete disregard for the  position of the Chinese side and blind opposition to WAPI</em></strong><em>&nbsp;&nbsp;[March  21, 2006]</em></p></td>
                </tr>
                <tr>
                  <td width="46" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2">&nbsp;</td>
                  <td width="455" valign="top" bgcolor="#FFFFFF" class="style2"><p>Statement of China's  Broadband Wireless IP Standards Working Group, responding to ISO's rejection of  WAPI<a href="http://www.cbronline.com/article_news.asp?guid=94B6B4DA-43C2-42E1-97F1-5E5067790575">...Full Story</a></p></td>
                </tr>
